[0m[49m[39m  39,  52[0m:[39m[49m ## Root Cause (observed, not repaired)
[0m[49m[39m  40,  53[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  41,  54[0m:[39m[49m When a `MultiPart` is constructed in-process (as a client would build it),
[0m[49m[39m  42,  55[0m:[39m[49m each `BodyPart` stores the raw Java object passed to its constructor as its
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 43     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m entity.  Here that object is `byte[]`.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m entity — here `byte[]`.
[0m[49m[39m  44,  57[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  45,  58[0m:[39m[49m On the server side, Jersey's `MultiPartReader` (`MessageBodyReader<MultiPart>`)
[0m[49m[39m  46,  59[0m:[39m[49m deserialises the HTTP wire bytes and wraps each part's content in a
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 47     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m `BodyPartEntity` that exposes an `InputStream`.  That HTTP round-trip never
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m `BodyPartEntity` that exposes an `InputStream`. That HTTP round-trip never
[0m[49m[39m  48,  61[0m:[39m[49m happens in a plain unit test, so:
[0m[49m[39m  49,  62[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  50,  63[0m:[39m[49m 1. `(BodyPartEntity) bodyPart.getEntity()` → `ClassCastException: [B cannot be
[0m[49m[39m  51,  64[0m:[39m[49m    cast to BodyPartEntity` — the entity is still `byte[]`.
[0m[49m[39m  52,  65[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  53,  66[0m:[39m[49m 2. `bodyPart.getEntityAs(BodyPartEntity.class)` → `IllegalStateException:
[0m[49m[39m  54,  67[0m:[39m[49m    Entity instance does not contain the unconverted content` — `getEntityAs`
[0m[49m[39m  55,  68[0m:[39m[49m    requires the entity to be stored as raw bytes (the "unconverted" wire form),
[0m[49m[39m  56,  69[0m:[39m[49m    which is only the case after the `MessageBodyReader` has parsed the stream.
